#!/usr/bin/env bash
# fsgg-coord — the ADR-0034 §4.4 resolver: find the typed engine and exec it, nothing else.
#
# WHY THIS EXISTS. Phase D of ADR-0040 replaced ~7,000 lines of `bash scripts/fsgg-coord` with the
# compiled `fs.gg.coord.cli` (`fsgg-coord-engine`). ADR-0034's decision 2 keeps the `scripts/fsgg-coord`
# PATH that every doc, workflow, and skill references — as a small bash SHIM that resolves the tool from
# `.config/dotnet-tools.json` (already distributed to every receiver by `sync-build-config.sh`, already
# watched by Renovate) and `exec`s it. The kit row, its digest, and its exec bit are unchanged; the shim
# stops churning, so the kit stops re-drifting on every protocol edit.
#
# THIS IS THE SWAP (ADR-0040 Phase D.2), NOW FINAL (D.4). This file WAS ~7,000 lines of bash; it is now
# a ~50-line resolver, proven transparent by `tests/coord-engine-parity/shim.sh` — the D.1 corpus is
# green THROUGH it. D.4 (the one-way door) deleted the old bash monolith and the shadow/differential gates
# that drove it; the engine is the one and only implementation now. Nothing that calls `scripts/fsgg-coord`
# had to change: this PATH still answers, and it answers with the engine.
#
# WHAT IT DOES. It resolves ONE engine and execs it, passing argv through unchanged and returning its exit
# code unchanged. It is a transparent pipe — it adds no output of its own on the happy path and holds no
# state. The resolution order is:
#
#   1. THE EXPLICIT BIN      — `FSGG_COORD_ENGINE_BIN`. An instruction. Honoured or REFUSED, never fallen
#                              back from: a caller who named an engine that is not there must be told, not
#                              silently handed a different (perhaps stale) build that answers for the one
#                              they meant.
#   2. THE SOURCE BUILD      — `src/FS.GG.Coord.Cli/bin/Release/net10.0/`, when THIS checkout is the one
#                              that builds the engine. `.github` alone does, and it never consumes the feed
#                              (ADR-0034 decision 2): *"the publish cycle is broken by asymmetry — `.github`
#                              builds the engine from source and never depends on the feed… a broken feed
#                              therefore cannot prevent the coordination tool from being fixed."* So where a
#                              source build exists it is the AUTHORITY, and it outranks both packaged forms.
#   3. a global tool on PATH — `dotnet tool install -g`, or any binary an operator put on PATH.
#   4. a LOCAL tool manifest — the receivers' shape: `.config/dotnet-tools.json` + `dotnet tool run`. A
#                              restored local tool is NOT on PATH (it answers only to `dotnet tool run`),
#                              so a manifest that DECLARES the engine but has not been restored is restored
#                              here — a manifest is a wish until `dotnet tool restore` grants it (#655).
#
# THE NUMBERS MOVED, AND #1018 IS WHY (old → new: 4 → 2, 2 → 3, 3 → 4; tier 1 is unchanged). The source
# build used to be LAST, beneath both packaged forms — an order "lifted verbatim from bash's proven
# `engine_resolve`" into the one repo where it asserts the opposite of what the ADR decided. In a RECEIVER
# that order is right and is retained: there is no source build, so a packaged engine is the only engine.
# In `.github` it inverted decision 2 outright — a FEED build beat the authoritative source, so this repo
# silently DID depend on the feed, and a fix sitting in `src/` never ran. Prose in #929, #1008 and #1018
# predates the move and says "tier 4" for what is now tier 2; the NAMES above cannot rot, so prefer them.
#
# MEASURED, AND THE SAME CAUSE BOTH TIMES. A global tool on PATH and a current `src/` both answered
# `--version` `0.3.0.0` and nothing warned, so `done --flip` falsely closed epic #889 — with the #1005
# guard that would have refused it sitting BUILT in `src/` (#1018). The same preemption then reached this
# shim's OWN tests: `tests/coord-engine-parity/shim.sh` builds a synthetic source-build checkout and drives
# the shim at it with `env -u FSGG_COORD_ENGINE_BIN`, but unsetting tier 1 was never enough — a global tool
# won, and the staleness legs made 2 REAL claims against the live board while passing vacuously (#1008).
# One cause, and it is the ORDER, not the guard: the guard was never mis-scoped, it was unreachable.
#
# A resolution that finds nothing is a hard error naming what to do — never a silent no-op, which is the
# #266 failure this whole effort exists to end.
#
# IT DECIDES TWO THINGS ABOUT COORDINATION, AND ONLY BECAUSE NOTHING ELSE CAN (#929, #709). `BOARD_WRITES`
# below names which verbs write shared state, so a STALE engine can be refused one; and an engine built
# from UNCOMMITTED source is warned about. That is coordination knowledge in a pipe that is meant to hold
# none, and the trade is deliberate: neither check can live in the engine, because the suspect engine IS
# the thing being checked — an engine built before the check existed would not run it, which is exactly
# how a fix for #914 sat in `src/` while the fleet ran without it. The resolver is the last place that
# sees both the artifact and the source before the exec.
#
# The two are one question asked at two joints — "is the code about to run the code this checkout says?"
# `stale_guard` compares the ARTIFACT to the source; `dirty_guard` compares that SOURCE to HEAD. Neither
# subsumes the other, and a build satisfies the first while defeating the second (see #709 below).
#
# NEITHER ASKS "IS IT ON MAIN?", AND THIS COMMENT MUST NOT IMPLY THEY DO. Both compare against the local
# checkout — the artifact to `src/`, `src/` to HEAD — so a worker who COMMITS kit WIP on a branch here,
# or whose shared checkout simply sits behind `origin/main`, defeats both while running code the fleet
# never merged. That gap is real and deliberately unclosed: the honest comparison is against
# `origin/main`, which is a network read this resolver must not do on every invocation, and which would
# fire on every checkout that is merely BEHIND — the normal state of a shared checkout nobody fetches. What is
# left is a guard that catches the observed bug (#709's ` M scripts/fsgg-coord`) and does not pretend to
# be a merge check.
set -uo pipefail

die() { echo "fsgg-coord: $*" >&2; exit 69; }  # EX_UNAVAILABLE — the engine is not here

git_toplevel() { git rev-parse --show-toplevel 2>/dev/null || true; }

# THE SHARED CHECKOUT'S WORKING TREE — the one every worker's worktree hangs off (#931).
#
# `git worktree list` reports the MAIN working tree FIRST, always and by documented contract, and as an
# ABSOLUTE path from anywhere. That is the whole reason it is spelled this way rather than the obvious
# `dirname "$(git rev-parse --git-common-dir)"`, which LOOKS equivalent and is not: `--git-common-dir`
# answers RELATIVE from the main checkout (a bare `.git`, measured), so `dirname` yields `.` — and `.`
# is the CALLER's tree, not the shared one. That would make the fallback below resolve to whatever tree
# the caller happens to be standing in, silently, exactly when it is meant to reach past it.
#
# `--porcelain`, because the human form appends `[branch]`/`(bare)` decorations that would land in the
# path. `cut -f2-` rather than `awk '{print $2}'`: a checkout path may contain spaces, and taking only
# field 2 would truncate it to the first word — a path that then fails `-x` and reads as "no build".
shared_toplevel() { git worktree list --porcelain 2>/dev/null | head -1 | cut -d' ' -f2- ; }

# The source build's path under a given working tree. ONE spelling, used by both tiers below: two
# copies of it is one edit away from a fallback that probes a path the primary tier does not, which
# would resolve a DIFFERENT engine than the one the guards just measured.
engine_path() { printf '%s/src/FS.GG.Coord.Cli/bin/Release/net10.0/fsgg-coord-engine' "$1"; }

# THE ARTIFACT IS NOT A REF (#929). Tier 2 execs a BUILD OUTPUT, and nothing keeps it in step with the
# `src/` beside it: `git pull` does not rebuild it, `git status` cannot see it, and `--version` answers
# the same assembly version from every build ever made — `0.2.0.0` when this line was written, `0.3.0.0`
# today, and never once a per-commit answer, which is the whole point rather than a detail that rotted.
# (#1018 measured exactly that: a global tool and a current `src/` both said `0.3.0.0`, hours apart in
# build time.) So a worker can run — and WRITE TO THE BOARD WITH — code that is
# not in their own tree. Twice on 2026-07-16 a stale engine silently ignored `release --status`, putting
# a merged item back to `Ready`: #914's own fix, absent from an engine whose `src/` contained it.
#
# READS WARN, WRITES REFUSE. A stale read misinforms one worker; a stale board write corrupts state the
# whole fleet shares, and twice it did. Refusing every stale exec instead would halt every worker the
# moment anyone touches `src/`, on a repo whose premise is N workers in one checkout.
#
# ONLY THE SOURCE BUILD, AND STRUCTURALLY SO — BUT THE STRUCTURE HAD TO BE BUILT, AND #1018 IS THE BILL
# FOR ASSUMING IT. This paragraph read: "the receivers' shape has no `src/` beside it to be stale against,
# and never reaches here — tiers 1-3 `exec` first." Every clause was TRUE. The inference was not: it needs
# "a checkout WITH a `src/` beside the binary therefore resolves this tier", and under the old order it did
# not — a global tool exec'd first whether or not `src/` was there. So the one shape that CAN be stale was
# the one shape that never reached the guard, and the sentence justifying the scoping named the very thing
# defeating it ("tiers 1-3 `exec` first") as its reason to be safe. It described the code its author meant
# to write. It is true NOW because the source build IS tier 2, and only tiers 3/4 — the receivers' shape,
# which has no source to be stale against — sit below it. An explicit FSGG_COORD_ENGINE_BIN is untouched
# either way: it is an instruction, and honouring it is tier 1's rule.
#
# THE VERB IS ALWAYS `$1`, and that is the engine's rule rather than an assumption of ours: it dispatches
# on argv[0] and REFUSES a flag before the verb (`unknown command: --repo`). So reading `$1` is exactly as
# strict as the engine's own dispatch — there is no accepted invocation that hides a write verb elsewhere,
# which is what would make this guard fail OPEN. Matching any argv token instead would fail the other way,
# on values: `ready --status Done` is a read, and `Done` is a write verb's name.
BOARD_WRITES=" claim take release heartbeat adopt add set-field flush child widen say done reap "

# STAT THE .dll, NOT THE APPHOST. `fsgg-coord-engine` is the .NET apphost — a fixed ~78 KB native stub,
# BYTE-IDENTICAL across every build of every commit. The IL, which is the thing that goes stale, is in
# `fsgg-coord-engine.dll` beside it. A guard that measured the apphost would be green on this exact bug.
#
# THE CLI's .dll IS THE WHOLE GRAPH'S BUILD STAMP. Cli references Core and GitHub, so a change anywhere
# under `src/` forces its recompile (verified: touching Core/Protocol.fs alone moves it). So comparing
# every `src/**/*.fs` against it neither false-greens on a Core-only edit nor false-STALEs after a real
# build — the false-stale being the one that would halt the fleet.
#
# PORTABLE `find`, AND THAT IS NOT PEDANTRY — IT IS THIS GUARD'S OWN FAILURE MODE. The obvious spelling
# ends `-print -quit`, stopping at the first hit. `-quit` is GNU-only: BSD/macOS find REFUSES it, and
# since the probe must swallow stderr (a missing src/ is a legitimate no-op, not an error), the refusal
# is invisible — the probe yields nothing, "nothing" reads as "not stale", and the guard SILENTLY never
# fires. Measured: with a -quit-refusing find on PATH, a board write ran on a genuinely stale engine, no
# warning, no refusal. That is the #266 signature this guard exists to END, rebuilt inside the guard. So
# no `-quit`: `head -1` bounds it instead, and the scan is ~30 files.
stale_guard() {
  local top="$1" dll="$2" verb="$3" newer built changed detail
  [ -f "$dll" ] || return 0   # no IL to measure against; the exec below fails honestly on its own
  newer="$(find "$top/src" -name '*.fs' -newer "$dll" -print 2>/dev/null | head -1)"
  [ -n "$newer" ] || return 0                                        # the engine is current — say nothing
  # `date -r FILE` is GNU; BSD's `-r` takes SECONDS. A failure here must not blank the message, so fall
  # back to '?': the timestamps are evidence, but the VERDICT above is what has to survive a foreign date.
  built="$(date -r "$dll" '+%Y-%m-%d %H:%M' 2>/dev/null || echo '?')"
  changed="$(date -r "$newer" '+%Y-%m-%d %H:%M' 2>/dev/null || echo '?')"
  detail="            engine built $built
            ${newer#"$top/"} changed $changed
            You are about to run code that is NOT in this checkout (#929). Rebuild it:
              dotnet build src/FS.GG.Coord.Cli -c Release"
  case "$BOARD_WRITES" in
    *" $verb "*)
      die "REFUSED — '$verb' writes the board the whole fleet shares, and the engine is STALE.
$detail" ;;
  esac
  echo "fsgg-coord: WARNING — the engine is STALE, so it need not behave as this checkout reads." >&2
  printf '%s\n' "$detail" >&2
  echo "            Board writes are refused until you do." >&2
}

# AND THE SOURCE IS NOT A REF EITHER (#709). `stale_guard` asks one question — "is the ARTIFACT behind
# the source?" — and it is an mtime question. It cannot ask the other one: "is the SOURCE ITSELF on
# main?" So the two states it separates are not the two that matter:
#
#   edited, NOT built   → .fs newer than .dll  → stale_guard fires.  The engine is the OLD, merged code.
#   edited AND built    → .dll newer than .fs  → stale_guard SILENT. The engine is somebody's WIP.
#
# The guard is loudest in the safe case and mute in the dangerous one. Building is what a worker does
# NEXT, so #929's window closes itself: the warning decays into silence exactly as the risk arrives.
#
# THE RISK IS THIS REPO'S ALONE, AND IT IS THE WHOLE FLEET'S. Every worker on this board runs the
# SHARED checkout's engine. Under `src/` live the scheduler, the claim CAS and the board writer. So one
# worker editing the kit here, in violation of pnext-item §2, silently hands every other worker an
# untested build of the lock they are about to take. #709 observed it live: ` M scripts/fsgg-coord` in a
# checkout the reporter had not touched, discovered only because they diffed it against HEAD afterwards.
#
# WHY they all run it moved, and the guard's subject did not. This paragraph used to say "a worktree has
# no bin/, so the source build cannot resolve there (that is why §2's isolation does not isolate this)"
# — true when written, and #931's tier 2b is precisely the repair of it: a worktree caller now RESOLVES
# the shared build rather than dying 69 at it. The conclusion is unchanged and is now a property of the
# resolver rather than an accident of where `bin/` happens to be, so tier 2b passes $SHARED to this
# guard — the reader standing in a worktree is exactly the reader whose claims that WIP is deciding.
#
# WARN, NEVER REFUSE — and this is NOT #929's trade repeated with a new subject. #929 may refuse a
# board write because its remedy is local, cheap and yours: rebuild, and you are clear. Dirtiness has
# no such exit. The checkout is dirty because somebody ELSE is mid-edit, and nothing you can run will
# clean it — so refusing would let one worker's §2 violation halt every OTHER worker's board writes,
# a fleet-wide outage manufactured by the guard rather than the bug. It would also trap the kit's own
# author, who is the one person who must be able to test an engine that is by definition uncommitted.
# The filer reached the same answer (#709: "my weak preference is warn always, refuse never").
#
# NO HEAD, NO VERDICT. A checkout with no commit has no baseline to be dirty AGAINST, so there is
# nothing to assert — the same shape as `stale_guard`'s "no IL to measure against" above, and as
# `release`'s "a column we cannot read is not one we may overwrite" (#331). This is also what keeps the
# receivers' shape silent: tiers 3/4 never reach here at all.
#
# A LINKED WORKTREE IS THE SANCTIONED FLOW, SO IT IS EXEMPT — and getting this wrong would aim the
# guard at the one worker obeying the rule it enforces. pnext-item §2 orders you to work the item in a
# worktree; a kit author who does that and builds there makes the source build resolve THERE, against a tree
# their own correct edits have made dirty. Warning them would accuse them of the §2 violation they are
# in the middle of avoiding, and there is nothing to warn about: no other worker resolves an engine
# through their worktree, so the WIP is reachable by nobody but them. Only the MAIN checkout is shared,
# and only its dirt is everyone's problem. `--git-dir` == `--git-common-dir` is exactly that question
# (they diverge in a linked worktree and nowhere else), which is why this is a git question and not a
# guess about paths.
#
# `status --porcelain`, NOT `diff --quiet`: it sees STAGED work (a `git add`ed WIP is still not on
# main) and untracked files, which `diff` alone cannot. `bin/` and `obj/` are gitignored, so the build
# every worker performs is invisible to it — the difference between a guard and a permanent false
# positive. Measured at ~3ms.
#
# AND `-c status.showUntrackedFiles=normal`, BECAUSE THE LINE ABOVE WAS NOT TRUE ON ITS OWN (#1043).
# "it sees … untracked files" is a claim about the CALLER'S CONFIG, not about `status`: `--porcelain`
# is a FORMATTING flag and does not override `status.showUntrackedFiles`. Set it to `no` — the usual
# remedy for a slow `git status` on a big repo, and inherited from ~/.gitconfig, which the shared
# checkout does not control — and this probe returns EMPTY on a tree full of uncommitted WIP. "Empty"
# then reads as "clean" at the `[ -n "$dirty" ]` below, and the guard SILENTLY never fires: #266's
# signature, rebuilt inside the check written to end it. Measured against a real tier-2 checkout with an
# untracked `New.fs`: default warns `1 path(s)`, `showUntrackedFiles=no` says NOTHING AT ALL.
#
# This is the `-quit` trap immediately above, and the `--no-optional-locks` trap below, wearing a third
# hat — and it is why they are worth spelling out rather than deleting as pedantry. All three are the
# same bug: a probe whose failure is INVISIBLE, so its silence is indistinguishable from a clean tree.
# The author reasoned it out twice for `find` and for a git flag, and the config channel kept the hole.
#
# `normal`, NOT `all`: it preserves exactly today's counting — a wholly-untracked directory stays
# collapsed to one entry — so `$n path(s)` and the `head -5` truncation below are byte-identical on any
# machine that never set the option. This forces the ANSWER's scope; it does not widen it.
#
# AND `core.excludesFile` IS LEFT ALONE — DECIDED, not overlooked (#1043 asked; this is the answer). It is
# the obvious next knob: a global ignore also hides files from `status`, so why force one and not both?
# Because THEY ARE NOT SYMMETRIC, and the difference is the whole design of this guard. Forcing
# `showUntrackedFiles` can only ever reveal files that are genuinely uncommitted and NOT ignored — every
# path it adds is real dirt, so it cannot produce a false positive. Forcing `core.excludesFile=/dev/null`
# would resurrect whatever the WORKER chose to ignore globally: measured, a `Protocol.fs.swp` beside a real
# source file reports as `?? src/…/Protocol.fs.swp` and warns about an editor swapfile that never reaches
# the engine. That is a permanent false positive on somebody's editor, and this guard cannot afford one —
# a warning that fires when nothing is wrong is one the fleet learns to skim, and the next one is real.
# (The repo's OWN `.gitignore` — `bin/`, `obj/` — is unaffected by either knob: measured, `bin/artifact`
# stays invisible with `excludesFile` forced off, so the build every worker performs stays invisible too.)
# The trade is a far-fetched miss (a worker whose global ignore matches `*.fs`) against a plausible false
# alarm. Take the miss.
#
# AND PLAIN `status`, DELIBERATELY — no `--no-optional-locks`. It looks made for this caller, and it is
# the `-quit` trap above wearing a different hat: it is git 2.19+, and on anything older it is an
# unknown option, which this probe's necessary `2>/dev/null` would swallow — leaving `$dirty` empty,
# "empty" reading as "clean", and the guard SILENTLY never firing. The contention it would avoid does
# not exist: measured with `.git/index.lock` HELD, `status` still answered correctly and exited 0,
# because refreshing the index is *optional* and git simply skips the write. A real portability hole
# traded for an imaginary lock.
#
# SCOPED TO WHAT ACTUALLY ENDS UP IN THE ENGINE, which is more than `src/`. The root
# `Directory.Build.props`, `Directory.Packages.props` and `global.json` are imported implicitly by every
# project beneath them, so a dirty package pin or SDK band changes the compiled engine exactly as an
# edited `.fs` does — and #672 (the ADR-0032 shared-build-config rollout) is an epic whose whole subject
# is editing those files. Naming only `src/` would have left the guard blind to part of its own subject:
# #266's signature, rebuilt inside the check written to end it. A pathspec that matches nothing is
# lenient (exit 0, no output), so naming a file this repo may not have costs nothing.
dirty_guard() {
  local top="$1" dirty n detail
  git -C "$top" rev-parse --verify -q HEAD >/dev/null 2>&1 || return 0
  [ "$(git -C "$top" rev-parse --git-dir 2>/dev/null)" \
    = "$(git -C "$top" rev-parse --git-common-dir 2>/dev/null)" ] || return 0
  dirty="$(git -C "$top" -c status.showUntrackedFiles=normal status --porcelain -- \
             src scripts/fsgg-coord Directory.Build.props Directory.Packages.props global.json 2>/dev/null)"
  [ -n "$dirty" ] || return 0
  n="$(printf '%s\n' "$dirty" | wc -l | tr -d ' ')"
  detail="$(printf '%s\n' "$dirty" | head -5 | sed 's/^/              /')"
  [ "$n" -gt 5 ] && detail="$detail
              … and $((n - 5)) more"
  echo "fsgg-coord: WARNING — this engine is built from UNCOMMITTED code (#709)." >&2
  echo "            $n path(s) that end up INSIDE the engine are modified in this SHARED checkout:" >&2
  printf '%s\n' "$detail" >&2
  echo "            Somebody is working the kit here, which pnext-item §2 forbids. Every worker on this" >&2
  echo "            board runs THIS scripts/fsgg-coord, so that WIP — the scheduler, the claim CAS, the" >&2
  echo "            board writer — is deciding your claims too. If it is yours: move it to a worktree." >&2
  return 0
}

# AN EXPLICIT PATH IS AN INSTRUCTION, NOT A HINT (bash's rule, kept exactly): if it is set and not runnable,
# REFUSE — do not fall through to some other engine the caller did not choose.
if [ -n "${FSGG_COORD_ENGINE_BIN:-}" ]; then
  [ -x "${FSGG_COORD_ENGINE_BIN}" ] || die "FSGG_COORD_ENGINE_BIN is set but not executable: ${FSGG_COORD_ENGINE_BIN}"
  exec "${FSGG_COORD_ENGINE_BIN}" "$@"
fi

TOP="$(git_toplevel)"

# TIER 2 — THE SOURCE BUILD, AND IT OUTRANKS EVERY PACKAGED ENGINE (#1018, #1008). `.github`'s shape: the
# engine built from source, never from the feed (ADR-0034 decision 2). This is the ONE tier with a `src/`
# beside the binary, so it is the one tier that can be STALE against it (#929) — and therefore the one that
# must be REACHED, which beneath a global tool it was not.
#
# THE CONDITION IS THE BUILD, NOT A REPO NAME, and that is precisely what keeps this off receivers. Only
# the repo that owns coord's source can have `src/FS.GG.Coord.Cli/bin/Release/net10.0/fsgg-coord-engine`
# under its toplevel; a receiver cannot, so it falls to tiers 3/4 exactly as before and its resolution is
# byte-for-byte unchanged. There is no `.github` special-case here to drift out of step with the roster.
#
# AND ONLY WHEN IT IS BUILT — an unbuilt `src/` falls through, deliberately. Decision 2's invariant is that
# a broken feed cannot prevent coord being FIXED, and building is the act of fixing: a fix you have built is
# a fix this tier protects; a fix you have not built is not yet running anywhere, and there is nothing to
# prefer it over. So a fresh clone with a global tool keeps working, and `die()` below still names
# `dotnet build` when nothing resolves at all.
#
# AN OPERATOR WHO GENUINELY WANTS THE PACKAGED ENGINE HERE IS NOT TRAPPED — tier 1 outranks this, and it is
# the documented way to mean it rather than to get it by accident:
#   FSGG_COORD_ENGINE_BIN="$(command -v fsgg-coord-engine)" scripts/fsgg-coord …
if [ -n "$TOP" ]; then
  CANDIDATE="$(engine_path "$TOP")"
  if [ -x "$CANDIDATE" ]; then
    # DIRTY BEFORE STALE, because a dirty checkout is usually WHY an engine is stale, and a refusal is
    # easier to act on when the thing that caused it is already on screen. `stale_guard` may die(); this
    # one never does, so it cannot swallow that refusal.
    dirty_guard "$TOP"
    stale_guard "$TOP" "${CANDIDATE}.dll" "${1:-}"
    exec "$CANDIDATE" "$@"
  fi
fi

# TIER 2b — THE SHARED CHECKOUT'S BUILD, FOR A CALLER STANDING IN A WORKTREE (#931).
#
# WHAT WAS BROKEN. `/pnext-item` §2 MANDATES an item worktree ("never work an item in the shared
# checkout"), and a fresh worktree has no `bin/`. So tier 2a missed, tier 3 found no global tool, tier 4
# found no manifest (`.github` has none — its engine is tier 2a), and the resolver died 69 for EVERY
# worker following the recipe. The tool printed dozens of commands into that: `fsgg-coord-engine <verb>`
# is 127 (`command not found`), and `scripts/fsgg-coord <verb>` was 69 — a MORE convincing failure,
# because it looks like a real diagnostic. Both spellings were broken, which is why printing the other
# one was not a fix and this tier is. (#931 says "25 sites"; it was 31 by the time it was worked, across
# verbs the issue never named. The thesis survived the drift; the count did not, so no number is pinned
# here for the next reader to re-check — `check-worker-id-attractor.py` rule 5 counts them at run time.)
#
# DECIDED ON THE RECORD, not chosen here (#931). Three alternatives were weighed and rejected: shipping
# the engine on PATH (a provisioning change, and it would make #569's fix wrong); printing
# `scripts/fsgg-coord` and stopping (still 69 — the trade this tier exists to refuse); an absolute path
# at runtime (correct, and unpasteable into any doc). This one fixes every site without changing what
# any of them print, and RETIRES the tribal note — *"run coord from the shared checkout"* — that every
# bitten worker was carrying privately. #570: a rule enforced by whoever happens to remember it decays.
#
# AFTER 2a, NEVER BEFORE IT. A worker who builds in their own worktree gets THEIR build — that is the
# kit author's whole workflow, and preempting it would hand them the shared engine and silently discard
# the edits they are testing. The consequence — a worker who edits `src/` here but does not build gets
# the shared engine, which does not carry their edits — is the status quo of the note this retires, not
# a regression this introduces.
#
# THE GUARDS MEASURE THE SHARED TREE, AND THAT IS LOAD-BEARING RATHER THAN TIDY. Passing "$TOP" here
# would compare the CALLER's `src/` against the SHARED build — and `git worktree add` writes every file
# at checkout time, so a fresh worktree's `.fs` mtimes are NEWER than any shared `.dll` by construction.
# `stale_guard` would fire on EVERY fresh worktree, and it REFUSES board writes: a guard that halts the
# entire fleet the moment it starts working, fail-closed, hiding inside an obviously-correct-looking
# line. The honest question is the same one tier 2a asks — "is THIS artifact behind the source beside
# IT?" — and both halves of that pair live under $SHARED.
#
# AND THE DIRTY GUARD NOW REACHES ITS REAL SUBJECT. `dirty_guard` exempts a linked worktree because
# nobody else resolves an engine through it. That premise held only while a worktree resolved NO engine;
# this tier is exactly the case where the shared checkout's WIP decides a worktree worker's claims, so
# `dirty_guard "$SHARED"` is the #709 warning arriving at the reader who needs it. It fires by the same
# rule, not an exception to it: $SHARED is a main working tree, so its `--git-dir` and `--git-common-dir`
# agree and the exemption simply does not apply.
# Only ASK when there is a git repo to ask about. `$TOP` empty means `rev-parse` already failed, so
# `git worktree list` would fail too — and this line is on the RECEIVERS' hot path, where tiers 3/4
# answer and every invocation would otherwise pay for a subprocess that cannot succeed.
SHARED=""
[ -n "$TOP" ] && SHARED="$(shared_toplevel)"
if [ -n "$SHARED" ] && [ "$SHARED" != "$TOP" ]; then
  CANDIDATE="$(engine_path "$SHARED")"
  if [ -x "$CANDIDATE" ]; then
    dirty_guard "$SHARED"
    stale_guard "$SHARED" "${CANDIDATE}.dll" "${1:-}"
    exec "$CANDIDATE" "$@"
  fi
fi

# TIER 3 — a global tool (or any operator-placed binary) on PATH.
if command -v fsgg-coord-engine >/dev/null 2>&1; then
  exec fsgg-coord-engine "$@"
fi

if [ -n "$TOP" ]; then
  # TIER 4 — THE RECEIVERS' SHAPE. Check the MANIFEST before probing `dotnet tool run` blindly — a `run` on
  # a repo with no manifest is a slow, noisy failure, and `.github` (whose source build is tier 2 above) has
  # no root manifest at all.
  MANIFEST="$TOP/.config/dotnet-tools.json"
  if [ -f "$MANIFEST" ] && command -v dotnet >/dev/null 2>&1 \
     && jq -e '.tools | to_entries[] | select(.value.commands // [] | index("fsgg-coord-engine"))' \
          >/dev/null 2>&1 <"$MANIFEST"; then
    # A MANIFEST IS A DECLARATION, NOT AN INSTALLATION (#655). If the tool is not yet restored, `dotnet tool
    # run` prints a restore hint and exits 1 — so restore it once (bookkeeping, in a subshell), then exec.
    # Asking a worker to restore has a measured hit rate of zero; do it for them.
    # `--` here is PROPHYLACTIC, not a fix: measured on dotnet 10.0.302, `tool run` does NOT consume
    # `--version` (unlike `--help`/`-h`, which it does — see the exec below, #1029). It is separated anyway
    # because this probe FAILS OPEN if that ever changes: a consumed `--version` would answer 0 from dotnet
    # itself, the shim would read "already restored" and skip the restore, and the exec would then fail with
    # the very hint this branch exists to pre-empt. One separator costs nothing and removes the whole class.
    if ! ( cd "$TOP" && dotnet tool run fsgg-coord-engine -- --version ) >/dev/null 2>&1; then
      # THE RESTORE'S OWN DIAGNOSIS IS THE EVIDENCE — DO NOT DISCARD IT AND THEN GUESS (#957).
      #
      # This was `>/dev/null 2>&1 || die "… the feed is unreachable or the version is unpublished"`:
      # the restore's words thrown away, and TWO causes asserted from an exit code. Both are false for
      # the failure that actually fires — a missing credential for the auth-walled org feed, which says
      # `401 (Unauthorized)` in as many words. The cause that fires was not in the list, and the list
      # was not observed. That is #266's class (a check reporting a cause it structurally cannot see),
      # and it fails toward the two LEAST actionable readings: told "the feed is unreachable" a worker
      # checks their network; told "the version is unpublished" they go read the release workflow.
      # Neither is the remedy, and the real one was named nowhere. It cost the reporter a debugging
      # pass on an otherwise-clean checkout.
      if ! restore_out="$( cd "$TOP" && dotnet tool restore 2>&1 )"; then
        # A HINT IS KEYED OFF THE OUTPUT, NEVER ASSERTED BLIND — that asymmetry IS the fix. Output we
        # do not recognise gets NO cause: the restore's own words are the finding, and inventing one on
        # top of them is the bug being removed. The two original causes survive here, demoted from
        # fallback to what they always should have been — claims made only when something observed
        # supports them.
        # MATCH ON THE PHRASE, NEVER ON A BARE STATUS NUMBER. `*401*` would fire on any output that
        # happens to contain those three digits — a hash, a version, a tmpdir called `tmp.401xyz` — and
        # then assert an auth failure nobody observed. That is this block's own bug, one level down, so
        # the patterns below are anchored to text NuGet actually emits.
        hint=""
        case "$restore_out" in
          *"401 (Unauthorized)"*|*Unauthorized*)
            hint="

  This is an AUTH failure, not an unreachable feed. The org feed (nuget.pkg.github.com) refused the
  credentials. Export FSGG_PACKAGES_ACTOR (your GitHub login) and FSGG_PACKAGES_READ_TOKEN (a PAT with
  read:packages) — a receiver's nuget.config reads them as %FSGG_PACKAGES_ACTOR% / %FSGG_PACKAGES_READ_TOKEN%." ;;
          *"403 (Forbidden)"*|*Forbidden*)
            hint="

  The credential was ACCEPTED and is missing the scope: FSGG_PACKAGES_READ_TOKEN needs read:packages." ;;
          *"Unable to load the service index"*|*"No such host"*|*"Name or service not known"*|*"Connection refused"*|*"timed out"*)
            hint="

  The feed is genuinely unreachable — this one IS a network fault, and the message says so because the
  restore's output said so." ;;
          *"is not found in NuGet feeds"*|*"Unable to find package"*)
            # The first pattern is the wording NuGet ACTUALLY emits — measured by driving a manifest that
            # declares a version no feed carries, not guessed. The obvious `Unable to find package` never
            # fired against the real thing; it is kept because `dotnet tool install` does use it. A hint
            # branch that cannot match is the same fail-open shape as the assertion this whole block
            # replaces, so these patterns are observations, not expectations. A bare `*404*` was dropped
            # for the reason given above the `case`.
            hint="

  The version declared in the manifest is not on the feed. This is the 'unpublished' case, claimed here
  only because the restore reported it." ;;
        esac
        die "the engine is declared in $MANIFEST but 'dotnet tool restore' failed:

$restore_out$hint"
      fi
    fi
    # exec from the ORIGINAL cwd, not $TOP: `dotnet tool run` finds the manifest by walking up from here,
    # and the engine is cwd-sensitive (reap scopes to the checkout you stand in, #480; the git-remote repo
    # default reads it, #430). A cd to $TOP would silently rescope those commands.
    #
    # `--` IS LOAD-BEARING, AND ITS ABSENCE IS WHY THIS SHIM WAS NOT THE TRANSPARENT PIPE ITS HEADER
    # PROMISES (#1029). `dotnet tool run` has its OWN `-?, -h, --help` option, so without a separator it
    # CONSUMES those flags and answers for itself — the engine is never reached. Measured on dotnet
    # 10.0.302, and it is not position-dependent (`… fsgg-coord-engine next --help` is eaten too):
    #
    #   dotnet tool run fsgg-coord-engine --help        -> dotnet's own help, EXIT 0
    #   dotnet tool run fsgg-coord-engine next --help   -> dotnet's own help, EXIT 0
    #   dotnet tool run fsgg-coord-engine -- next --help -> reaches the engine
    #
    # Exit 0 is what made it silent: the worker asked the coordination tool for help, got dotnet's, and
    # nothing reported a failure. THIS repo cannot reproduce it — `.github` builds from source and resolves
    # at tier 2, which is a real `exec` — so the only repo that owns the shim is the one repo where the bug
    # is invisible, and every RECEIVER got dotnet's help instead (ADR-0034 decision 2).
    exec dotnet tool run fsgg-coord-engine -- "$@"
  fi
fi

die "no fsgg-coord engine found. Set FSGG_COORD_ENGINE_BIN, install the tool (dotnet tool install), restore the local manifest (dotnet tool restore), or build it from source (dotnet build src/FS.GG.Coord.Cli -c Release)."
